Check the Date Picker with NVDA on Windows

NVDA Setup

I run Parallels on my Mac, a commercial software application which allows me to run Windows as a virtual machine.

Once the Windows VM is running, the NVDA screen reader software can be downloaded and installed for free. I prefer to use NVDA with a Windows hardware keyboard plugged into my Mac, although it’s not a requirement.

Of course if you’re already on a Windows machine, you can install NVDA and you’re good to go.

To begin testing, launch NVDA and open Chrome on Windows.

Navigating with NVDA

There’s some crossover in screen reader navigation commands. Tab and the Arrow keys navigate through interactive and static content similarly to VoiceOver. But there are also major differences in Windows screen readers, including interaction modes.

On the CampSpots homepage, Tab through the elements until you reach the “Where to?” input.

When NVDA reaches the input, a sound similar to a cash register will play.

This will alert you that NVDA has left “Browse mode” and is in now in “Focus mode” (a.k.a. “Forms mode”). Focus mode is activated automatically when the user’s focus point enters certain types of elements, such as inputs and textareas.

While in Focus mode, any key you type will be passed directly through the browser to the currently focused element. For example, hitting “H” on the keyboard will type an H value into the input.

On a Windows keyboard, hitting Insert + SPACE will toggle between interaction modes. On a Mac laptop keyboard, Fn + Enter + Space will do the same action. (You can also configure keys as you prefer, such as mapping Caps Lock for Insert.)

In contrast to Focus mode, hitting “H” on the keyboard in NVDA’s Browse mode jumps you to the next heading.

Modes Affect Interaction

In its default Browse mode, using the right and left Arrow keys, NVDA will read one letter at a time. The up and down Arrow keys will navigate through static and interactive content.

For situations where you’ve built a custom interactive component that uses Arrow keys–such as our date picker–the behavior in a Windows screen reader might not be what you expect. More on this in a moment.

If you run into this behavior, use Insert + SPACE to switch into Focus mode and try again to see if the interaction works as expected.

Checking the Date Picker with NVDA

Navigating to the Listings Detail Page

With NVDA open, use the Tab and Enter keys to navigate from the homepage to the Listings page by way of the MegaNav (”Plan Your Trip” > "Find a camping spot”). Tab onto the first Listing for Cranberry Lake and activate the link with the Enter key to navigate to it.

When you use the “Skip to Main Content” link, NVDA will start reading the content inside the main landmark as focus is sent to this wrapping element. Keep Tabbing through the Listing Detail page to reach the date picker component.

Operating the Date Picker

When focus gets to the < Jun button, NVDA announces “Previous month June, button.” Another Tab makes it announce “Next month August, button.”

Tabbing again into the calendar grid, it announces semantic details about the table (”seven rows and seven columns”) and that focus is in “row two, Sunday, column one, June 26th button”.

What we won’t hear is the automatic mode change “cash register” sound from NVDA.

This tells us that NVDA is still in Browse mode.

Recall from earlier that in Browse mode, the left and right Arrow keys tell NVDA to advance one character at a time. So hitting the right Arrow key won’t advance to the next day, although incidentally the down Arrow does.

When you hit Insert + SPACE on a Windows keyboard to enter Focus mode, you should be able to navigate the date picker as expected with the left and right Arrow keys.

Learning More about NVDA

In addition to the NVDA docs, NVDA’s public Issue Tracker on GitHub is a useful resource for learning from people who both use and build the software. There are insightful threads from developers looking to build sites that support its use, highlighting how NVDA was designed and often working as expected.

In one particular issue, a developer posted about how using Arrow keys in a gridcell was reading one letter at a time instead of moving to the next interactive element as they expected from their code.

As it happens, the NVDA developers noted the behavior but found that users of the software didn’t want it to work that way! They preferred to explicitly enter Focus mode as opposed to activating it automatically for that pattern.

This is another example of the importance of getting input from people who rely on Assistive Technology and not assuming we know how things should operate as developers.
